153400cd-98f8-5dbf-9063-4e2f1e902457.message: Bugfix h2c upgrade process with request body  Requests with a body and h2c upgrade headers are a pain, as the body must be fully received over HTTP/1.1 before the upgrade response is sent, the connection is upgraded and the correct response sent via HTTP/2. This is a pain as Quart can't both upgrade and wait for the body.  As h2c is a niche use case (most HTTP/2 clients, including all browsers don't support it), Quart will take the easy option and ignore the upgrade header if a request has a body. Should a client really want this, the client should send a pre-flight options request to upgrade the connection and then send the actual request with the body.

5ad649c1-b316-5099-b3dc-b9283660dd76.message: Bugfix app.run SSL usage and Hypercorn compatibility  Version 0.4.0 of Hypercorn onwards stopped accepting SSL contexts and instead accepted the configuration of the context (to build the context itself). This change was made as the SSL context setup is quite involved for HTTP/2. In order to fix in Quart the run interface has been changed to accept the SSL configuration rather than a SSL context. This also (necessarily) bumps the minimum Hypercorn version to 0.4.0.
5ad649c1-b316-5099-b3dc-b9283660dd76.title: Bugfix app.run SSL usage and Hypercorn compatibility

b7cd46d3-dd4c-5eb6-be55-c04088f5d5f3.title: Add values attribute on Requests

bd1ba975-b764-5d38-9a62-d83c3374699c.message: Add the ability to send conditional responses  This allows a response to be made conditional (with a similar API to Werkzeug) thereby allowing a correct response to range requests. It differs from Werkzeug in that a maximum partial size can be specified in order to limit the size of a request (regardless of the requested range). The primary usage of this is for static files e.g. videos and hence the ability to seek on a file is utilised for better performance.
bd1ba975-b764-5d38-9a62-d83c3374699c.title: Add the ability to send conditional responses

bdbe9f61-617e-5026-828f-7fd43d5ce990.message: Add samesite cookie support  The attribute `samesite` specifies that the browser is not allowed to send the cookie along with cross-site requests. This helps to mitigate CSRF attacks. Valid values for this attribute are "Strict" and "Lax".  A new config value, `SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE`, that's null by default, determine the `samesite` attribute for the app's cookies.  Note: this update relies on a feature that is present in Python >= 3.8.  See:  * https://gitlab.com/pgjones/quart/issues/220 * https://bugs.python.org/issue29613
bdbe9f61-617e-5026-828f-7fd43d5ce990.title: Add samesite cookie support

0f9b40a2-00b5-531c-9edc-a77f339773ca.title: Use copy of sys.modules.items() to avoid runtime error

3ad71cf5-45fa-531a-ab10-faf037e1931b.message: Make the session interface async  This is a backwards incompatible change to the SessionInterface that makes the ``open_session``, ``close_session`` and ``make_null_session`` methods async. This allows for async session stores such as aioredis or asyncpg to be used (rather than the default pure cookie system).

0620ab8c-12eb-54ea-8d61-94f76fc2b45d.message: Refactor push promise API  This adds supports for copying certain request headers to the push promise (in order to mimic the requester having sent the push request). The chosen headers match those chosen by mod_h2.  This removes the response push_promises functionality on the basis that push promises are related to the request, not the response, and as doing so allows for a better API.  Finally this allows for push promises to be tested using the testing client (or manually if creating Request classes).
0620ab8c-12eb-54ea-8d61-94f76fc2b45d.title: Refactor push promise API

7d5b390b-9d31-5c8b-9c00-c0f5e85e21c8.message: Refactor to mitigate DOS attack  This is aimed to mitigate an attack whereby a client requests a route that is known to stream a large amount of data e.g. a video, and stops reading from its socket. This results in back-pressure to the Quart server which would previously just continue to write to the socket and fill in memory buffers. With enough connections and large enough streaming responses this could exhaust the host memory and crash the server.  To mitigate this the Quart Serving code now responds to the asyncio pause_writing and resume_writing callbacks by clearing and setting an awaitable event. This event can then be awaited (in a drain call) during streaming, therefore preventing further writes till the back pressure is reduced. This is similar to the undocumented `_drain_helper` method on asyncio protocols.

1deb526e-98d5-531c-b356-64ec85a67ca8.message: Unblock logging I/O by logging in separate threads  Create a new private function `_setup_logging_queue` that is used by both `create_logger` and `create_serving_logger`.  The function creates a new instance of `LocalQueueHandler`, that is a slightly modified version of `QueueHandler` to avoid record preparation (no need for handling records within the same process). It starts a new `QueueListener` associated to the same queue, that will handle the logging I/O asynchronously.  Note: two different `QueueListener` instances will handle logs respectively from the `quart.app` logger and the `quart.serving` logger.  Resources:  * https://www.zopatista.com/python/2019/05/11/asyncio-logging/ * https://docs.python.org/3/howto/logging-cookbook.html * https://docs.python.org/3/library/logging.config.html * https://docs.python.org/3/library/logging.handlers.html

727bffde-7f01-57a2-9f43-4f7290b606a7.message: Improve extensibility  This allows extensions to change more of the Quart application functionality especially changing class that have some dependence on asyncio primitives or the loop itself. This will then allow an extension that replaces all the asyncio parts with trio parts (for example).  There are two backwards incompatible changes, firstly the websocket test client usage changes from,     with test_client.websocket('/ws/') as test_websocket:        ...  to become async, i.e.     async with test_client.websocket('/ws/') as test_websocket:        ...  additionally the Websocket class now takes a Callable[Awaitable] rather than a Queue on initialisation.  Note it also changes the testing client class to use the application defined websocket class (rather than the Quart default).

7f438de2-95c9-540b-ad63-1003b825b5c8.message: Bugfix a get_data call  e5a690d420f771492a3b54388caf537a4547b453 introduced an attempt to fix this, but in fact missed the actual issue which is that if the Werkzeug HTTPException could not be imported it was set to be ``object``. If the code was correct only the Werkzeug HTTPExceptions would trigger the get_data call, and would not require an await.

e39cf079-303f-598c-820f-14989643d7b2.message: Bugfix ensure sync functions work with async signals  A sync function when connected to an async signal is wrapped in a coroutine. Blinker by default takes weak reference to the connected receiver, which in the case of the coroutine is problematic as it ceases to exist before sync function does. To work around this the coroutine is placed onto an attribute of the sync function, thereby ensure it exists as long as the sync function does. (Ideally I'll think of a better way).

0ff25294-7a95-5249-bbfb-e804687dfd5b.message: Redirect with a 308 rather than 301  With strict slashes enabled and the route defined with a trailing slash e.g. `/a/` a request to `/a` currently results in a 301 response to redirect to `/a/`. This is good for GET and HEAD requests, but problematic for other verbs as clients will typically treat a 301 response as meaning redirect as a GET verb as noted in RFC 2616 section-10.3.2 (RFC 2616 stated this was erroneous, and then RFC 7231 allowed this behaviour). RFC 7538 later introduced a 308 code to work as 301 was originally intended. As 308 is now widely supported, 301 can be changed to 308.  This follows an equivalent commit in Werkzeug
0ff25294-7a95-5249-bbfb-e804687dfd5b.title: Redirect with a 308 rather than 301

a073c0ce-45c3-5147-9bb8-ad0e02e58ed5.message: Bugfix ensure the ASGI callable returns on completion  Previously the callable would only return on receipt of a disconnect message, rather than returning either on a disconnect or when the handling is complete.  Note that there is an intentional optimisation to ignore any disconnect messages and simply run the handling to completion in the case of http requests. This is to improve performance, which would suffer significantly with the multi task approach required for websockets.
a073c0ce-45c3-5147-9bb8-ad0e02e58ed5.title: Bugfix ensure the ASGI callable returns on completion

e7ae1d5b-56f6-5546-8ef1-8cf226dfa42e.message: Run synchronous code via a Thread Pool Executor  This ensures that any synchronous functions passed to Quart are run in an executor, rather than wrapped in a coroutine and run in the event loop (as before). This should help users that cannot escape some synchronous code (presumed to be a third party library) yet still want to use Quart.  I've chosen to copy the contexts to the exector as discussed in https://bugs.python.org/issue34014 as I think this is expected and least surprising.  The ensure_coroutine method is a method so that it can be overriden by extensions, most notably the Trio extension which cannot use the asyncio executor system.  The signal version does not provide a simple way to override in extensions, and it is a bit of a special case. Therefor I've left it as is - but I intend to remove it in a later version.

a5fda43a-782e-511c-9943-05f94210686e.message: Bugfix websocket socket.close exception errors  In a tight loop such as      @app.websocket('/ws')     async def ws():         while True:             await websocket.send('hello')  control is never yielded back to the event loop, which prevented the transport from closing and resulted in many `socket.send() raised exception.` warnings. a7ad8c94-c356-5575-9684-f324f2d064d4.message: Ensure flash works when imported via flask  Flash is a coroutine that expects to be run within the request context which means it cannot be synchronously called from flask based code. To fix this a sync wait wrapper is added to the flask_patch system.

dc70d8a2-b3a8-5f1f-ad89-4b46bfd700d5.message: Support ASGI root_paths  This is implemented such that it adds it as a root_path to the paths that Quart is trying to match against the incoming request. If the request does not have the root_path at its root then a NotFound exception is raised on matching. This allows the same app to mounted multiple times with different root paths as configured by the server.

3b2cba35-19b1-5b4e-a2f0-5f69fdb48112.message: Initial ASGI support  This adds initial support of ASGI, allowing ASGI servers such as uvicorn and daphne to be used with Quart. To do so requires the Quart instance (typically called ``app``) to be wrapped in a ASGIServer as so      # main.py      from quart.serving import ASGIServer      app = Quart(__name__)     ...     asgi_app = ASGIServer(app)  and then uvicorn (and others) can be used via      uvicorn main:asgi_app  Note that this is provisional, and I will likely change (or have to change) this API.  Uvicorn has a real advantage in that it uses httptools rather than h11 to parse HTTP/1, which is quicker (although less robust). It has the disadvantage that HTTP/2 is not supported.
3b2cba35-19b1-5b4e-a2f0-5f69fdb48112.title: Initial ASGI support

85aef023-7c4d-5701-b224-60c521794de2.message: Bugfix cancel the stream get in Body iteration  Previously when the body is complete the body awaitable would return and leave the stream.get awaitable unawaited. 29c5a58b-cb80-51d8-a260-7e8e21f36b96.message: Add a timeout to the request get_data method  This should wrap all the standard (Flask/Werkzeug API) body retrieval methods and attributes (e.g. data, form, get_json) with a protective timeout. As desired for Quart the body attribute usage is not protected and instead left to the user (with doc warnings). This should allow very fine control over how the body is consumed.

e054ff73-4400-5f7b-8af2-ae42bd2624ce.message: Initial support of host matching and subdomains  Quart, does not need the full host matching and subdomain options present in Werkzeug as Flask only really allows host matching for the SERVER_NAME in the app config, rather than for any server name. This means that a host for the URL Rule is automatically created from the SERVER_NAME if absent and that the host is only matched against the request host if host matching is enabled.

668c269a-5e87-55b5-88b2-0e9d905e5fd7.message: Bugfix websocket handling  This ensures that only a full message is passed through to the websocket queue (rather than every frame). It also ensures that the connection is closed and the task cancelled.  With this the autobahn testsuite fuzzyclient tests pass (as with wsproto).
668c269a-5e87-55b5-88b2-0e9d905e5fd7.title: Bugfix websocket handling

b912dec3-25c7-513d-8f5b-03b65b2c4619.message: Bugfix ensure request body iteration returns all data  Previously it could miss the final bytes received if the completion flag was also set (with the append) before yielding to the event loop. This was possible as the completion took precedence over finishing the iteration.

9d53b370-492d-5ba1-9926-8fd8376147eb.message: Add the ability to stream with context  This allows for a route function to return an async generator that has access to the request context (which is normally not possible as the context is removed with the return of the response).

0955fc39-f3bf-566e-834a-b3eaac21beb3.message: Expand the abort functionality and signature  The Werkzeug version effectively takes the code, and optionally description and a complete reponse object. As these are the constructor arguments for the Werkzeug HTTPException class. I've followed the principle (abort takes HTTPException class constructor arguments) but this means that the Quart version takes a code and optionally a description and name.
0955fc39-f3bf-566e-834a-b3eaac21beb3.title: Expand the abort functionality and signature

55f05b66-94d7-5ce4-9feb-5c98df88b3c8.message: Bugfix incorrect endpoint overwrite error for wrapped view functions  A synchronous view function is wrapped with a coroutine in the add_url_rule method, which results in a different handler for each addition. This was problematic when the same synchronous view function is added multiple times for multiple routes as the handler would differ for each addition and hence result in an overwrite assertion error.  This commit solves the problem by knowing if a handler is in fact a wrapper added by Quart and if so comparing against the wrapped view function.
55f05b66-94d7-5ce4-9feb-5c98df88b3c8.title: Bugfix incorrect endpoint overwrite error for wrapped view functions
